@realmoney "Buyers Live Higher and Sellers Live Lower" @realmoney Subscribers should now be familiar with the above adage that I coined a few years ago in my Diary. The derivation of my saying is based on the proliferation of investment products and strategies that worship at

the altar of price momentum. In our brave new investment world, price is not truth - distortions and artificiality in prices (abetted by ETFs and risk parity, etc.) provide opportunity to the emotionless trader and investor. Charts, in my view, have increasingly lost their

@realmoney Hey, Cody... What's The Hardest Trade? In the formative years of TheStreet in the late 1990s I used to pen a columnb called the "Hardest Trade." It started like this, "Hey Cody, what's the hardest trade today?" Whatever the hardest trade (my fellow contributor) Cody

Willard answered with, was often the best and most profitable trade. So... "Hey Cody, what's the hardest trade?" Cody Willard is no longer writing for TheStreet (but I will tweet this out so hopefully he will answer it) - in his absence, I will try to answer the question myself:

In my view the hardest trade is to stay with (and not sell the) stocks that were recently purchased and have had reasonably large percentage gains in the last few trading sessions. Wait, on reflection, the hardest trade might be buying stocks after the large advance.

And buying now may pay even greater dividends for the intermediate term investor - and, maybe even, for the short term trader. It's the hardest trade. @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @business @ScottWapnerCNBC @codywillard @Sarge986 @michaelsantoli

@realmoney The Merchants Of Attention * So much is said confidently in the financial media. * Much of it is "made up." Repeating for emphasis. To almost a person, the talking heads who have been recently parading on the stage of financial media all say (in a very confident

manner) that this is a great time to "upgrade one's portfolio." I counted eleven money managers who said exactly the same thing over the last two days on financial television. I presume that means to buy high quality companies with deep business moats - that have strong balance

sheets and abundant financial resources. Historically, at "a" market bottom that is precisely the wrong strategy. The stocks that perform the best out of "a" or "the" bottom are some of the more leveraged companies who's shares have been hardest hit in a bear market.
